 {"id":"asupersync-n6kwt.6","title":"[WASM][SharedWorker] Ship a same-origin coordinator/pool reuse lane with explicit fallback","description":"Productize SharedWorker as an optional same-origin coordinator and pool-reuse lane for Browser Edition. The value proposition is not "background magic"; it is amortized worker startup, multi-tab reuse, and centralized browser-side coordination when the host supports SharedWorker. The lane must remain truthful about browser constraints and must automatically fall back to dedicated-worker or inline execution when SharedWorker is unavailable, policy-disabled, version-incompatible, or unhealthy.","design":"Treat SharedWorker as a topology optimization layered on top of the execution ladder, not as a semantic fork. Define one same-origin coordinator per application/version scope, explicit client registration and deregistration, protocol version negotiation, crash/reconnect behavior, and downgrade paths back to dedicated-worker or inline lanes. Keep ownership, cancellation, and replay semantics equivalent to lower lanes even though the hosting topology changes.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Browser Edition has a self-contained SharedWorker lane plan with explicit prerequisites and downgrade behavior.
2. SharedWorker usage never broadens the project's correctness claims beyond what lower lanes can already prove.
3. Multi-tab reuse, version mismatch, and worker loss all have explicit fallback stories instead of undefined behavior.","notes":"This branch exists because SharedWorker can materially improve real browser deployments, but only if it is framed as an optional same-origin coordinator rather than a hand-wavy replacement for browser limits.","status":"tombstone","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-16T17:09:53.545102132Z","created_by":"SageOwl","updated_at":"2026-03-23T07:08:28.669231976Z","closed_at":"2026-03-23T07:08:28.669231976Z","source_repo":".","deleted_at":"2026-03-23T07:08:28.669209654Z","deleted_by":"system","delete_reason":"merge deletion","original_type":"task","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["browser","fallback","sharedworker","vnext","wasm"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-n6kwt.6","depends_on_id":"asupersync-2jhnk.6","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-16T17:12:51.919954050Z","created_by":"SageOwl","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-n6kwt.6","depends_on_id":"asupersync-n6kwt","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-16T17:09:53.545102132Z","created_by":"SageOwl","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-n6kwt.6.1","title":"[WASM][SharedWorker] Define tenancy, lifecycle, and downgrade contract","description":"Define the SharedWorker tenancy, lifecycle, and security contract in a way that future implementation can follow mechanically. This bead should answer which browsing contexts may join, how app/version namespaces are partitioned, how client identity is tracked, how shutdown/quiescence map onto a shared coordinator, and which cases force immediate downgrade.","design":"Write a single contract covering same-origin scoping, version compatibility, port/session registration, client departure, coordinator idleness, and the rule that SharedWorker may disappear without violating semantics because the runtime can demote. Make explicit which state is ephemeral in-memory coordinator state versus durable state that must live elsewhere such as IndexedDB-backed artifacts. Include non-goals such as cross-origin federation and pretending SharedWorker exists on every browser.","acceptance_criteria":"1. There is one authoritative contract for SharedWorker scoping, lifecycle, and downgrade reasons.
